 and the response of audiences and critics to radical drama, this thoughtful study also demonstrates how theater functions in times of political repression. Despite his struggles, Holcroft also had major successes: this book examines his surprisingly robust afterlife, as his plays, especially The Road to Ruin, were repeatedly revived worldwide in the nineteenth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aEnglish dramay18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh  aThomas Holcroft, Treason Trials, melodrama, theater censorship, working-class life writing, William Godwin, Sir Thomas Lawrence, James Gillray, Robert Dighton, Richard Newton, Samuel de Wilde, William Mulready, radicalism, authorship, life writing, afterlives, The Road to Ruin, eighteenth-century theater, nineteenth-century theater, theater and performance, literary activism, 1790s, radical drama, eighteenth-century political activism.1 aGarnai, Amy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079130340uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978168448447840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781684484478423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781684484478/original  a978-3-11-079130-3  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK